p.jpg" decoding="async" width="92" height="172" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fd/Xerxes_I_tomb_Lydian_soldier_circa_470_BCE_cleaned_up.jpg/138px-Xerxes_I_tomb_Lydian_soldier_circa_470_BCE_cleaned_up.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fd/Xerxes_I_tomb_Lydian_soldier_circa_470_BCE_cleaned_up.jpg/184px-Xerxes_I_tomb_Lydian_soldier_circa_470_BCE_cleaned_up.jpg 2x" data-file-width="696" data-file-height="1302" /></a></span></div><div class="thumbcaption text-align-center">Lydian soldier of the <a href="/wiki/Achaemenid_army" class="mw-redirect" title="Achaemenid army">Achaemenid army</a>, <abbr title="circa">c.</abbr><span style="white-space:nowrap;">&#8201;480 BC</span>.. <a href="/wiki/Xerxes_I" title="Xerxes I">Xerxes I</a> tomb relief.</div></div><div class="tsingle" style="width:294px;max-width:294px"><div class="thumbimage" style="height:172px;overflow:hidden"><span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Satrapy_of_Lydia.jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e1/Satrapy_of_Lydia.jpg/292px-Satrapy_of_Lydia.jpg" decoding="async" width="292" height="172" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e1/Satrapy_of_Lydia.jpg/438px-Satrapy_of_Lydia.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e1/Satrapy_of_Lydia.jpg/584px-Satrapy_of_Lydia.jpg 2x" data-file-width="855" data-file-height="505" /></a></span></div><div class="thumbcaption text-align-center">Lydia, including Ionia, during the Achaemenid Empire.</div></div></div></div></div>
<p>The <b>Satrapy of Lydia</b>, known as <b>Sparda</b> in <a href="/wiki/Old_Persian" title="Old Persian">Old Persian</a> (<a href="/wiki/Old_Persian_cuneiform" title="Old Persian cuneiform">Old Persian cuneiform</a> <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%F0%90%8E%BF%F0%90%8E%B1%F0%90%8E%BC%F0%90%8E%AD" class="extiw" title="wikt:êéøêé±êéºêé≠">êéøêé±êéºêé≠</a>, <i>Sparda</i>),<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> was an administrative province (<a href="/wiki/Satrap" title="Satrap">satrapy</a>) of the <a href="/wiki/Achaemenid_Empire" title="Achaemenid Empire">Achaemenid Empire</a>, located in the ancient kingdom of <a href="/wiki/Lydia" title="Lydia">Lydia</a>, with <a href="/wiki/Sardis" title="Sardis">Sardis</a> as its capital.
</p>
<meta property="mw:PageProp/toc" />
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Achaemenid_satrapy">Achaemenid satrapy</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Lydia_(satrapy)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Achaemenid satrapy"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:DNa_Inscription_Sparda.jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d6/DNa_Inscription_Sparda.jpg/150px-DNa_Inscription_Sparda.jpg" decoding="async" width="150" height="53" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d6/DNa_Inscription_Sparda.jpg/225px-DNa_Inscription_Sparda.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d6/DNa_Inscription_Sparda.jpg/300px-DNa_Inscription_Sparda.jpg 2x" data-file-width="496" data-file-height="176" /></a><figcaption>The name for Lydia as an Achaemenid territory in the <a href="/wiki/DNa_inscription" title="DNa inscription">DNa inscription</a> of <a href="/wiki/Darius_the_Great" title="Darius the Great">Darius the Great</a> (<abbr title="circa">c.</abbr><span style="white-space:nowrap;">&#8201;490 BC</span>): <i>Sparda</i> (<a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%F0%90%8E%BF%F0%90%8E%B1%F0%90%8E%BC%F0%90%8E%AD" class="extiw" title="wikt:êéøêé±êéºêé≠">êéøêé±êéºêé≠</a>).</figcaption></figure>
<p><a href="/wiki/Tabalus" title="Tabalus">Tabalus</a>, appointed by <a href="/wiki/Cyrus_the_Great" title="Cyrus the Great">Cyrus the Great</a>, was the first satrap; however, his rule did not last long as the Lydians revolted. The insurrection was suppressed by general <a href="/wiki/Mazares" title="Mazares">Mazares</a> and his successor <a href="/wiki/Harpagus" title="Harpagus">Harpagus</a>. After Cyrus' death, <a href="/wiki/Oroetus" title="Oroetus">Oroetus</a> was appointed as satrap. Oroetus ruled during the reign of <a href="/wiki/Cambyses_II" title="Cambyses II">Cambyses</a>, and after the chaotic period that followed the Persian king's death, he conquered the <a href="/wiki/Greece" title="Greece">Greek</a> isle of <a href="/wiki/Samos_Island" class="mw-redirect" title="Samos Island">Samos</a>, killing its ruler <a href="/wiki/Polycrates" title="Polycrates">Polycrates</a>. Due to his growing power, <a href="/wiki/Darius_the_Great" title="Darius the Great">Darius the Great</a> had <a href="/wiki/Bagaeus" title="Bagaeus">Bagaeus</a> kill Oroetus. Bagaeus himself may have become satrap for a short period, but the next rulers were <a href="/wiki/Otanes_(son_of_Sisamnes)" title="Otanes (son of Sisamnes)">Otanes</a> and Darius' younger brother, <a href="/wiki/Artaphernes" title="Artaphernes">Artaphernes</a>.
</p>
<h2><span id="Ionian_revolt_.28499_BC.29"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Ionian_revolt_(499_BC)">Ionian revolt (499 BC)</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Lydia_(satrapy)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Ionian revolt (499 BC)"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>During the <a href="/wiki/Ionian_revolt" class="mw-redirect" title="Ionian revolt">Ionian revolt</a> in 499 BC, Sardis was sacked by the Greeks. Five years later, the rebellion was suppressed and to the surprise of the Greek world, Artaphernes was very lenient in his treatment of the rebels.
</p><p>After this period, many Persians settled in Lydia. The worship of eastern gods such as <a href="/wiki/Anahita" title="Anahita">Anahita</a>, as well as <a href="/wiki/Persification" class="mw-redirect" title="Persification">persified</a> Lydian deities, began. Although members of the Persian aristocracy were given estates in the region following the Greek revolt, Greeks loyal to the Persian Empire were also given estates.
</p>
<h2><span id="Invasion_of_Greece_.28480-479_BC.29"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Invasion_of_Greece_(480-479_BC)">Invasion of Greece (480-479 BC)</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Lydia_(satrapy)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Invasion of Greece (480-479 BC)"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Preparations_of_Xerxes.jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/52/Preparations_of_Xerxes.jpg/220px-Preparations_of_Xerxes.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="179" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/52/Preparations_of_Xerxes.jpg/330px-Preparations_of_Xerxes.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/52/Preparations_of_Xerxes.jpg/440px-Preparations_of_Xerxes.jpg 2x" data-file-width="586" data-file-height="478" /></a><figcaption>Xerxes stationed in Sardis with all his invasion force during the winter of 481-480 BC.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Artaphernes was succeeded as satrap in 492 BC by his son <a href="/wiki/Artaphernes_II" class="mw-redirect" title="Artaphernes II">Artaphernes II</a>. Lydians enrolled in the <a href="/wiki/Achaemenid_army" class="mw-redirect" title="Achaemenid army">Achaemenid army</a>, and participated to the <a href="/wiki/Second_Persian_invasion_of_Greece" title="Second Persian invasion of Greece">Second Persian invasion of Greece</a> (480‚Äì479 BC). Sardis was where all the troops of Xerxes stationed during the winter of 481-480 BC to prepare for the invasion of Greece.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Achaemenid_Shekel.jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e6/Achaemenid_Shekel.jpg/220px-Achaemenid_Shekel.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="101" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e6/Achaemenid_Shekel.jpg/330px-Achaemenid_Shekel.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e6/Achaemenid_Shekel.jpg/440px-Achaemenid_Shekel.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1738" data-file-height="795" /></a><figcaption>Achaemenid Era silver shekel made in Sardis between 500 and 450 BC showing a warrior-king holding a bow and a lance.</figcaption></figure>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:CILICIA,_Soloi._Tiribazos,_Satrap_of_Lydia._Second_reign,_388-380_BC.jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/40/CILICIA%2C_Soloi._Tiribazos%2C_Satrap_of_Lydia._Second_reign%2C_388-380_BC.jpg/220px-CILICIA%2C_Soloi._Tiribazos%2C_Satrap_of_Lydia._Second_reign%2C_388-380_BC.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="118" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/40/CILICIA%2C_Soloi._Tiribazos%2C_Satrap_of_Lydia._Second_reign%2C_388-380_BC.jpg/330px-CILICIA%2C_Soloi._Tiribazos%2C_Satrap_of_Lydia._Second_reign%2C_388-380_BC.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/40/CILICIA%2C_Soloi._Tiribazos%2C_Satrap_of_Lydia._Second_reign%2C_388-380_BC.jpg/440px-CILICIA%2C_Soloi._Tiribazos%2C_Satrap_of_Lydia._Second_reign%2C_388-380_BC.jpg 2x" data-file-width="650" data-file-height="350" /></a><figcaption>Coinage of <a href="/wiki/Tiribazos" class="mw-redirect" title="Tiribazos">Tiribazos</a>, Satrap of <a href="/wiki/Lydia" title="Lydia">Lydia</a>, with <a href="/wiki/Ahuramazda" class="mw-redirect" title="Ahuramazda">Ahuramazda</a> on the obverse. <abbr title="circa">c.</abbr><span style="white-space:nowrap;">&#8201;388 ‚Äî 380 BC</span>.</figcaption></figure>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:IONIA,_Achaemenid_Period._Autophradates._Satrap_of_Sparda_(Lydia_and_Ionia),_circa_380s-350s.jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/88/IONIA%2C_Achaemenid_Period._Autophradates._Satrap_of_Sparda_%28Lydia_and_Ionia%29%2C_circa_380s-350s.jpg/220px-IONIA%2C_Achaemenid_Period._Autophradates._Satrap_of_Sparda_%28Lydia_and_Ionia%29%2C_circa_380s-350s.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="103" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/88/IONIA%2C_Achaemenid_Period._Autophradates._Satrap_of_Sparda_%28Lydia_and_Ionia%29%2C_circa_380s-350s.jpg/330px-IONIA%2C_Achaemenid_Period._Autophradates._Satrap_of_Sparda_%28Lydia_and_Ionia%29%2C_circa_380s-350s.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/88/IONIA%2C_Achaemenid_Period._Autophradates._Satrap_of_Sparda_%28Lydia_and_Ionia%29%2C_circa_380s-350s.jpg/440px-IONIA%2C_Achaemenid_Period._Autophradates._Satrap_of_Sparda_%28Lydia_and_Ionia%29%2C_circa_380s-350s.jpg 2x" data-file-width="800" data-file-height="374" /></a><figcaption>Coin of <a href="/wiki/Autophradates" title="Autophradates">Autophradates</a>, Achaemenid Satrap of Sparda (<a href="/wiki/Lydia" title="Lydia">Lydia</a> and <a href="/wiki/Ionia" title="Ionia">Ionia</a>), <abbr title="circa">c.</abbr><span style="white-space:nowrap;">&#8201;380 ‚Äî 350 BC</span>.</figcaption></figure>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Persepolis_stairs_of_the_Apadana_relief.jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/68/Persepolis_stairs_of_the_Apadana_relief.jpg/220px-Persepolis_stairs_of_the_Apadana_relief.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="147" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/68/Persepolis_stairs_of_the_Apadana_relief.jpg/330px-Persepolis_stairs_of_the_Apadana_relief.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/68/Persepolis_stairs_of_the_Apadana_relief.jpg/440px-Persepolis_stairs_of_the_Apadana_relief.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3509" data-file-height="2349" /></a><figcaption>Lydian delegation at Apadana, <abbr title="circa">c.</abbr><span style="white-space:nowrap;">&#8201;500 BC</span>.</figcaption></figure>
<p>From the period of 480 BC to 440 BC, there is little historical information about the satrap of Lydia. In 440 BC, the satrap <a href="/wiki/Pissuthnes" title="Pissuthnes">Pissuthnes</a> attempted to retake Samos, which had rebelled against <a href="/wiki/Athens" title="Athens">Athens</a>, but failed. In 420 BC, Pissuthnes revolted against the Persian king <a href="/wiki/Darius_II" title="Darius II">Darius II</a>. The Persian soldier and statesman <a href="/wiki/Tissaphernes" title="Tissaphernes">Tissaphernes</a> (Pers. TiŒ∏rafarna, Gr. Œ§ŒπœÉœÉŒ±œÜŒ≠œÅŒΩŒ∑œÇ), a grandson of <a href="/wiki/Hydarnes" title="Hydarnes">Hydarnes</a>, was sent by Darius II to Lydia to arrest and execute Pissuthnes. Tissaphernes became satrap of Lydia in 415 BC and continued to fight <a href="/wiki/Amorges" title="Amorges">Amorges</a>, son of Pissuthnes.
</p><p>After <a href="/wiki/Sparta" title="Sparta">Sparta</a> had defeated Athens, the Greeks invaded Lydia. Tissaphernes overcame the invasion of <a href="/wiki/Thimbron_(fl._400%E2%80%93391_BC)" class="mw-redirect" title="Thimbron (fl. 400‚Äì391 BC)">Thibron</a> in 399 BC but was defeated at Sardis by the Spartan King <a href="/wiki/Agesilaus_II" title="Agesilaus II">Agesilaus II</a>. The satrap was executed and replaced by <a href="/wiki/Tiribazus" title="Tiribazus">Tiribazus</a>, who restored order in Lydia and was responsible for a series of treaties between the Persian king and the Greek city states.
</p><p><a href="/wiki/Autophradates" title="Autophradates">Autophradates</a> was probably Tiribazus' direct successor, and was loyal to the Achaemenid monarch during a series of revolts in 370 BC. The last satrap of Lydia was <a href="/wiki/Spithridates" title="Spithridates">Spithridates</a>, who was killed by <a href="/wiki/Alexander_the_Great" title="Alexander the Great">Alexander the Great</a> at the battle of <a href="/wiki/Battle_of_the_Granicus" title="Battle of the Granicus">Granicus</a>.
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Satraps">Satraps</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Lydia_(satrapy)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Satraps"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
